
// revision of C concepts

c language keywords:

auto: auto defines automatic variables by default(local variables);
recreated everytime funtion is executed
// auto int var1;


break and continue: break statement terminates the innermost loop
when encountered; also terminates switch statement; continue
statement skips statement after it inside loop.

// for (i=1; i<=10; ++i)
   {
     if(i==3)
     continue;
     if (i==7)
     break;
     printf("%d ", i);
   }


output: when i is 3, the continue statement skips 3; when i is 7,
break effect acts to terminate the for loop.

// 1 2 4 5 6


switch, case and default: switch and case is used when block of
statement needs to be executed among many blocks.

// switch(expression)
   {
     case "1": //some statement to execute when 1
     break;
     case "5": //some statement to execute when 5
     break;
     default; //some statement to execute when default
  } 


char: char keyword defines variable type character.

// char alphabet;


const: const declares a read-only variable whose value cannot
be changed directly after initialization.

// cont int y = 5;


do and while: print the value of i till it is 9.

// int i = 0;
   do
   {
      printf("%d ",i);
      i++;
   }
  while (i < 10);





